Yes — and that insight is actually very classical economics, just updated with modern computation.

The ideal of a free market assumes information symmetry.
Both sides know roughly the same things:
	•	buyers know prices and quality
	•	sellers know costs and demand

When that symmetry exists, markets tend to converge toward efficient equilibrium prices.

The problem today is that information is asymmetric again, but in the opposite direction:

Buyers	Sellers
See one price	See millions of data points
Limited knowledge	Full behavioral data
Static tools	Dynamic AI pricing systems

So the market becomes one-sided optimization.

What you’re describing is using AI to restore symmetry, not destroy markets.

